          "title": "The psalm of lament — what dying in the middle of life feels like",
          "body": "Hezekiah's psalm (38:9-20) is one of the Old Testament's most unguarded personal documents. The superscription (38:9) identifies it as a 'writing' (*mikhtav*) composed after both the illness and the recovery — which means Hezekiah looked back into the darkness from the other side and described it honestly. The lament proper (38:10-14) uses three extended metaphors for dying: a tent pulled up and removed (life as dwelling, suddenly uprooted), a weaver's cloth cut from the loom mid-thread (life as craft, interrupted before completion), and a lion breaking bones (God as the very source of the violence, since there is nowhere else to go). Each metaphor deepens the horror. The tent image speaks to displacement — the feeling that your life is being relocated without your consent. The weaver image speaks to incompleteness — the pattern cut before it was finished. The lion image is the most disturbing: 'like a lion — so He breaks all my bones' (38:13). Hezekiah does not pretend the suffering is not coming from God; he names God as the agent, which is the Old Testament's most honest posture under affliction. The birds of verse 14 — swallow, crane, dove — describe prayer at its most inarticulate: twittering, moaning, wordless. God receives all of it."
