          "title": "The appendix — medicine and the sign requested",
          "body": "Verses 21-22 appear chronologically prior to the events of the chapter — they describe the fig-cake remedy and Hezekiah's sign-request, which in the parallel account of 2 Kings 20:7-8 occur before the reversal of the shadow. Isaiah places them after the psalm as an appendix, perhaps because the psalm is the chapter's theological climax and the appendix represents the narrative loose ends the psalm transcends. Two observations are theologically important. First, the fig-cake poultice (38:21) is a medical intervention prescribed by the prophet of God — the supernatural and the natural means of healing are not in competition. God reverses the shadow and prescribes a fig-cake; both are His instruments. This pattern resists both the mistake of bypassing medicine in favor of miracle and the mistake of trusting medicine as if no miracle is possible. Second, Hezekiah's sign-request (38:22) — 'what is the sign that I shall go up to the house of the LORD?' — reveals that his ultimate concern is not merely survival but restored access to temple worship. The house of the LORD is the destination (38:20, 22), the goal of recovery, the place where the vow of praise will be honored. Life is not valued for its own sake in this chapter; it is valued as the precondition for doxology."
